{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17475207","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17475207"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:30:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:30:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12551"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12551","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12551"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.02,0.39,0,0.55]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5050"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55220"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5050","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5050"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12551"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40738"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"152"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2453"},{"type":"tags","id":"6344"},{"type":"tags","id":"9270"},{"type":"tags","id":"9616"},{"type":"tags","id":"9689"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9197"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9751"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13118"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14623"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16797"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55220","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55220"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-day-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a 12-hour history of poor feeding and lethargy. He has been feeding much less and vomiting soon after feeds. He was born at term via emergency caesarean section due to prolonged rupture of membranes. His birth weight was 3.1 kg. The pregnancy was complicated by recurrent maternal urinary tract infections. There was no significant maternal illness or infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears lethargic with jaundiced sclera and mottled skin. His pulse rate is 165/min, blood pressure 98/65 mmHg, respiratory rate 66/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 39.5\u00b0C. His current weight is 2.7 kg.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA detailed septic profile has been sent. The neonate has been started on empiric intravenous antibiotic therapy as well as intravenous acyclovir. At this time, he is clinically improving, with normal observations and is more interactive. His laboratory results are shown:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete blood count\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 180 g/L (140-225)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count: 24 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (5-21)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelet count: 250 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (150-550)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECRP: 25 mg/L (\u0026lt;3)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrine Microscopy:\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWCC: 300 x10\u003Csup\u003E6\u003C/sup\u003E/L (0-10)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERCC: 6 x10\u003Csup\u003E6\u003C/sup\u003E/L (0-10)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEpithelial: 0 x10\u003Csup\u003E6\u003C/sup\u003E/L (0-10)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELumbar Puncture\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWCC 0 x10\u003Csup\u003E6\u003C/sup\u003E/L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERCC 0 x10\u003Csup\u003E6\u003C/sup\u003E/L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAppearance: Clear\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely focus of infection?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pneumonia","Meningitis","Group B Streptococcal sepsis","Acute otitis media","Urinary tract infection"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis neonate presents with signs of sepsis, which is one of the leading causes of morbidity and mortality among neonates if not diagnosed and treated promptly. Any neonate presenting with irritability, lethargy, or reluctance to feed could represent sepsis. Neonatal sepsis is categorised into two broad categories: early onset sepsis (birth to day 4 of life) and late onset sepsis (day 4 to day 28 of life).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENeonates with presumed sepsis require NICU admission, a complete septic workup (including a complete blood count, CRP, blood culture, urine culture, chest x-ray, and lumbar puncture) and initiation of IV antibiotics. First line antibiotics typically include IV ampicillin and IV cefotaxime.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrinary tract infection\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct response as the biochemical markers and urine microscopy point to this as the source. UTIs are the most common cause of serious bacterial infection in neonates. The presentation is typically non-specific. The urine microscopy shows a significantly elevated white cell count (300 x10\u003Csup\u003E6\u003C/sup\u003E/L), strongly indicating inflammation in the urinary tract.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E is less likely because there is no evident focus of infection involving the respiratory tract. Absence of grunting, significant hypoxemia, and any added sounds makes pneumonia a less likely cause as the primary focus of infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeningitis\u003C/strong\u003E is an important consideration in neonates 0-3 months of age presenting with fever. However, in this case, the lumbar puncture analysis is not suggestive of meningitis, with normal cell counts and clear appearance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGroup B Streptococcal sepsis\u003C/strong\u003E is possible but less likely because there is no evident history of maternal GBS colonisation. Additionally, GBS is an uncommon causative agent for UTIs. However, a negative blood culture would be needed to definitively rule this out.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute otitis media\u003C/strong\u003E is less common in neonates and there is another more likely source of infection in this case. Neonates with otitis media may present with irritability and inconsolable crying, which are not prominent features in this presentation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Neonatal sepsis is one of the leading causes of neonatal mortality.","Urinary tract infection is the most common cause of serious bacterial infection in neonates.","A complete septic workup is essential in neonates presenting with signs of sepsis."],"references":["Ershad M, Mostafa A, Dela Cruz M, Vearrier D. Neonatal Sepsis. Curr Emerg Hosp Med Rep. 2019;7(3):83-90. doi: 10.1007/s40138-019-00188-z. Epub 2019 Jun 19. PMID: 32226657; PMCID: PMC7100521.","Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne. Recognition of the seriously unwell neonate and young infant [Internet]. Melbourne (AUS): Royal Children\u0027s Hospital; [cited 2024 Oct 14]. Available from: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Recognition_of_the_seriously_unwell_neonate_and_young_infant/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40738"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12551"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20392"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20392","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20392"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/MjLCIz7h5kdcAW3quRqDg4W5Mz9tF4.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/MjLCIz7h5kdcAW3quRqDg4W5Mz9tF4.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":630,"height":565}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40738","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40738"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-14T11:50:06+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-14T11:50:06+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5050"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55220"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Di